T*
( 7. Generalisation, Trade-Offs, And Limitations) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The approach should generalise to bot traffic that is repetitive,) Tj
T*
(mechanically timed, or concentrated in narrow device and query patterns. It may) Tj
T*
(miss bots that deliberately randomise timing, distribute activity across many) Tj
T*
(query/domain pairs, or closely imitate human behaviour.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The main trade-off is explainability versus coverage. Rules are easier to) Tj
T*
(defend but can miss novel patterns. The anomaly model broadens coverage but) Tj
T*
(needs careful interpretation because it finds unusual events, not necessarily) Tj
T*
(fraudulent events.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Known limitations:) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(- There are no ground-truth labels, so measured precision, recall, and) Tj
T*
(  calibration cannot be reported.) Tj
T*
(- Legitimate campaigns can create high repetition, dense clusters, or regional) Tj
T*
(  concentration.) Tj
T*
(- The ct rule is supporting evidence only; it should not be used as a) Tj
T*
(  country-level blocking rule.) Tj
T*
(- The regular inter-arrival rule uses pseudo-session groups because there is no) Tj
T*
(  explicit user or session identifier.) Tj
T*
(- The anomaly score is relative to the current batch and should be monitored) Tj
T*
(  for drift across future runs.) Tj
T*
